Are public parks Accessible in Palm Beach County?¶

Analysis¶

Name: Wesnahika Charles

Github Webpage Link: https://nahika07.github.io/

Introduction¶

In this project the general question I want to solve over all would be, within Palm Beach County Florida, are the public parks here accessible, in the sense that, are they accessible to bus stops, residential areas, train stations, etc. I would also like to figure out exactly where in Palm Beach County has the most accessible public parks and which has the least accessible ones. I have already hypothesized that areas near downtown West Palm Beach may have the most accessible parks due to the high concentration of public transport, however, given how I have lived in the area for some time, the parks are still a quite a distance away from the actual area. I would also think that areas more out towards Lake Okeechobee would be less accessible to considering, from what I’ve seen, how semi-rural and sparsely populated it is.

The first piece of data I would utilize would be the basic location data of the parks in Palm Beach County sourced from the Florida Geospatial Open Data Portal. This will give me the name of the park, the address, the county (to which I would just filter on Palm Beach), the type of Park, whether it has a pool or as well as longitude and latitude. The question would be simple, what are the exact locations of these parks? This dataset would also help me figure out how many public parks we have in our county as well.

The second part of this project would be how we would gauge accessibility and we would need a couple of data sources for this. With open data coming from Palm Beach TPA, we will be able to derive the location of all Amtrak and Tri-Rail Stations in Palm Beach County, using the Palm Beach County Open Data Page, we could also extract the bus stops that are in the area, with this we would be able to look at the amount of bus stops that are nearest to each park. The question I would ask using these datasets would be how many of these transit areas are located around these parks, and which location, say for example municipality (at a general level) or park has the most transit stops closest to them. I believe I will most likely measure this by counting the amount of transit areas that are less than a 2-mile radius, I could also just convert the distance between two longitude and latitude points to get the number of miles as well.

I will be working on this project by myself, allocating several hours a week to working on it and making progress, I will employ the use of git as version control to make sure that my progress is being saved correctly om GitHub.

Milestone 2: Additional Extraction, Transform, and Load (ETL) + Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA), and Model Proposal¶

For my extra peice of data, I wanted to factor in Walkability score. The Walkability Score is a metric used to determine how far a given location is to nearby amenities. This score is calculated based on intersection denisity, reidential density, accessbility if amenities such as grocery, stores, restaurants, and of course, parks and recreational areas! I chose to incorporate walkability simply because I thought it would be an interesting criteria to add onto my analysis of whether or not certain parks are more accessible, considering how diverse given areas and locations are across palm beach county, I could imagine that looking at the walkability scores of the general location of each of these parks could give me a nice set number that could partially determine the accesibility value of each of these parks. One of the sources of this score would be www.walkscore.com/ that has several tables showcasing scores of different areas and states as well as allowing for a user to input a given location and fing out how walkable that location is, in order to access the data of for Palm Beach accounty, I decided to scrap a table that showcased the walkability score of cities in Florida and averaged it! Also, one thing about the way this source calculates walkability score is that it does not factor in public transportation. This is because there is another metric they use called "Transit" score! Such a score would be extremely useful for this project however, many of the park locations did not have a score assigned to them.

url = "https://www.walkscore.com/FL/"

# Step 2: Parse the HTML content
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

# Step 3: Find the table
# You may need to inspect the page to find the correct table
table = soup.find('table')  # Adjust if there are multiple tables or if the structure differs

# Step 4: Extract the headers
headers = []
for th in table.find_all('th'):
    headers.append(th.text.strip())

# Step 5: Extract the rows
data = []
for tr in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:  # Skip the header row
    row = []
    for td in tr.find_all('td'):
        row.append(td.text.strip())
    data.append(row)

# Step 6: Create a DataFrame

Scraping the WalkScore Website for each Parks Walkability score¶

In [20]:
import re

def get_walk_score(address):
    try:
        # Format the address for the URL
        formatted_address = address.replace(' ', '-')
        url = f"https://www.walkscore.com/score/{formatted_address}"
        
        # Send a GET request to the URL
        response = requests.get(url)
        
        # Check if the request was successful
        if response.status_code == 200:
            soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')
            
            # Locate the walk score image element
            score_img = soup.find('img', {'src': re.compile(r'/badge/walk/score/\d+\.svg')})
            if score_img:
                # Extract the score from the src attribute
                score_url = score_img['src']
                score = re.search(r'/badge/walk/score/(\d+)\.svg', score_url)
                if score:
                    return score.group(1)  # Return the score as a string
                else:
                    return None
            else:
                return None
        else:
            print(f"Failed to retrieve data for {address}, Status code: {response.status_code}")
            return None
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error fetching score for {address}: {e}")
        return None

# Add walk scores to the DataFrame
Palm_Beach_Parks['FullAddress'] = Palm_Beach_Parks['ADDRESS'].str.cat(Palm_Beach_Parks['CITY'], sep=' ')
Palm_Beach_Parks['WalkScore'] = Palm_Beach_Parks['FullAddress'].apply(get_walk_score)

As you can see by this map, regardless of walk score, all of the maps seems to be clustered around the eastern coast of the county, As one could probably see, as the parks move away from the coast and enter more into the center, you start to notice more red and yellow dots showing up. But what is super interesting is how some of of the more rural areas that border Lake Okeechobee like Pahokee and Belle Glade have parks with pretty high walkscores! In a way, this also makes sense considering how small, old and honestly neglected those towns are, these towns were created in the early 1900s ontop of already existing swamps and wetland, so much of these far west county towns have more compact city planning and honestly haven't changed since then.

Next Steps and Model Planning!¶

Eventually, I want to be able to create a classification model where I place them into buckets of "accessible" or "non-accessible" based on using a clusterring model. I choose an unsupervised clustering model simply because it would help me really answer my question, "Are Palm Beach Parks Accessible?" by using number of bus stops and accessibilty score I will be able to quantify how many parks indeed fit thus criteria. To do this, I would create some sort of criteria that would possibly include a park having at least 3 transit stops within 1.5 miles and walkability score of <50 has being an accesible park! Another alternative is I could do something similar, Clustering (K-Means) that would cluster parks into high, medium or low accessibility (an example of high would be a park that is located within 0.5 miles of a bus stop, medium would be 1-2 and low >2) which would also help in answering my question.

Calculating the number of Bus Stops per park within a 0.25 mile radius!¶

The first thing that I want to do is figure out how many bus stops exist for each park. In order to harnest this information, first I would need to classify what is considered a "walkable distance", many metrics, including our already existing walkability score, says that a "5 minute walk" or 0.25 miles is considered "comfortably walkable" to most Americans (https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3377942/). In order for me to figure out this information, I would need to use the longitudes and latitudes of both the parks and the bus stops, "cast" a 0.25 mile radius around each park, and whatever busstop is near that park, will be counted under a new column called "number of busstops".

from geopy.distance import geodesic

def count_busstops_within_radius(park_row, busstops_df, radius=0.25):
    park_location = (park_row['LAT_DD'], park_row['LONG_DD'])
    count = 0
    for _, busstop_row in busstops_df.iterrows():
        busstop_location = (busstop_row['LAT'], busstop_row['LON'])
        # Calculate distance
        distance = geodesic(park_location, busstop_location).miles
        if distance <= radius:
            count += 1
    return count

# Apply the function to each park
Palm_Beach_Parks['# of busstops'] = Palm_Beach_Parks.apply(
    count_busstops_within_radius, 
    axis=1, 
    busstops_df=PB_busstops_df
)

# Calculate correlation coefficient
correlation = Palm_Beach_Parks['WalkScore'].corr(Palm_Beach_Parks['# of busstops'])

# Fit a regression line
from scipy.stats import linregress
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = linregress(
    Palm_Beach_Parks['WalkScore'], Palm_Beach_Parks['# of busstops']
)

# Generate regression line values
Palm_Beach_Parks['Regression_Line'] = (
    slope * Palm_Beach_Parks['WalkScore'] + intercept
)

In [93]:
def map_cluster_to_accessibility(cluster):
    if cluster == 3:  # Bright yellow
        return 'Very High Accessibility'
    elif cluster == 2:  # Green
        return 'High Accessibility'
    elif cluster == 1:  # Teal
        return 'Medium Accessibility'
    else:  # cluster == 0 (Dark purple)
        return 'Low Accessibility'


Palm_Beach_Parks['Accessibility_Level'] = Palm_Beach_Parks['Cluster'].apply(map_cluster_to_accessibility)

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Group by city and cluster to count parks in each group
city_cluster_counts = Palm_Beach_Parks.groupby(['CITY', 'Accessibility_Level']).size().reset_index(name='Count')

# Total parks per city
city_totals = Palm_Beach_Parks['CITY'].value_counts().reset_index()
city_totals.columns = ['CITY', 'Total_Parks']

# Merge totals with the city-cluster counts
city_cluster_counts = city_cluster_counts.merge(city_totals, on='CITY')

# Calculate percentage for each cluster within a city
city_cluster_counts['Percentage'] = (city_cluster_counts['Count'] / city_cluster_counts['Total_Parks']) * 100

# Pivot for visualization
pivot_df = city_cluster_counts.pivot(index='CITY', columns='Accessibility_Level', values='Percentage').fillna(0)

# Plot a stacked bar chart
pivot_df.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(12, 6), colormap='autumn')
plt.title('Accessibility Level Breakdown by City')
plt.xlabel('City')
plt.ylabel('Percentage of Parks')
plt.legend(title='Accessibility Level', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

To conclude this project I decided to add this stacked bar chart that shows all of the cities and the proportion of accessibility they all share. Areas such as Palm Beach Shores and Latana seem to exclusively highly accessible parks, however areas such as Tequesta and Loxahatchee have exclusively little accessibilty. More larger and diverse areas like West Palm Beach, Boyton, Boca Raton, Lake Worth and Delray seem to have sizable representations of all 4 categories. Cities towns that have low accessibilty areas should perhaps incorporate better pedestrain sidewalk areas as well have the county expand the publc transportation to make sure that parks are closer to amenities and residential areas in order for all of its citizens to be able to properly enjoy them, a small local trolley system to help people move around, use up empty plots of land and create more recreational centeres, as well as widening sidewalks and encorporating more bike lanes would definiely help in solving this issue.
